"Covey C., Gleckler P.J., Phillips T.J., Bader D.C.","Secular trends and climate drift in coupled ocean-atmosphere general circulation models",2006,"Journal of Geophysical Research Atmospheres","111","3", D03107,"","",,,10.1029/2005JD006009,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33646244781&partnerID=40&md5=bbc4860f8e219ab7c711ca9f811559d2","Program for Climate Model Diagnosis and Intercomparison, Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, Livermore, CA 94550, United States","Covey, C., Program for Climate Model Diagnosis and Intercomparison, Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, Livermore, CA 94550, United States; Gleckler, P.J., Program for Climate Model Diagnosis and Intercomparison, Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, Livermore, CA 94550, United States; Phillips, T.J., Program for Climate Model Diagnosis and Intercomparison, Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, Livermore, CA 94550, United States; Bader, D.C., Program for Climate Model Diagnosis and Intercomparison, Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, Livermore, CA 94550, United States","Coupled ocean-atmosphere general circulation models (coupled GCMs) with interactive sea ice are the primary tool for investigating possible future global warming and numerous other issues in climate science. A long-standing problem with such models is that when different components of the physical climate system are linked together, the simulated climate can drift away from observation unless constrained by ad hoc adjustments to interface fluxes. However, 11 modern coupled GCMs, including three that do not employ flux adjustments, behave much better in this respect than the older generation of models. Surface temperature trends in control run simulations (with external climate forcing such as solar brightness and atmospheric carbon dioxide held constant) are small compared with observed trends, which, include 20th century climate change due to both anthropogenic and natural factors. Sea ice changes in the models are dominated by interannual variations. Deep ocean temperature and salinity trends are small enough for model control runs to extend over 1000 simulated years or more, but trends in some regions, most notably the Arctic, differ substantially among the models and may be problematic. Methods used to initialize coupled GCMs can mitigate climate drift but cannot eliminate it. Lengthy ""spin-ups"" of models, made possible by increasing computer power, are one reason for the improvements this paper documents. Copyright 2006 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Atmospheric temperature; Climate change; Climatology; Global warming; Oceanography; Sea ice; Time series analysis; atmosphere-ocean coupling; climate change; general circulation model; sea ice; secular variation; surface temperature",,,,,,"AchutaRao, K., Covey, C., Doutriaux, C., Fiorino, M., Gleckler, P., Phillips, T., Sperber, K., Bader, D., An appraisal of coupled climate simulations (2004), http://www-pcmdi.llnl.gov, PCMDI Rep. 71, UCRL-TR-202550, Lawrence Livermore Natl. Lab., Livermore, Calif (Available at)Bleck, R., Rooth, C., Hu, D., Smith, L.T., Salinity-driven thermocline transients in a wind- and thermohaline-forced isopycnic coordinate model of the North Atlantic (1992) J. Phys. Oceanogr, 22, pp. 1486-1505; Bryan, F.O., Climate drift in a multicentury integration of the NCAR Climate System Model (1998) J. Clim., 11, pp. 1455-1471; Cavalieri, D.J., Gloersen, P., Parkinson, C.L., Comiso, J.C., Zwally, H.J., Observed hemispheric asymmetry in global sea ice changes (1997) Science, 278, pp. 1104-1106; Collins, W.D., Hack, J.J., Boville, B.A., Rasch, P.J., Williamson, D.L., Kiehl, J.T., Briegleb, B., McCaa, J.R., Description of the NCAR Community Atmosphere Model (CAM2) (2003) Natl. Cent. for Atmos. Res., , http://www.ccsm.ucar.edu/models/atm-cam/index.html, Boulder, Colo. (Available at; Covey, C., The seasonal cycle in coupled ocean-atmosphere general circulation models (2000) Clim. Dyn., 16, pp. 775-